notes:
Two fragments edited by Israel Lévi (1900b), which may be considered lost. Re-edited by Bornstein (1904) 87-9.

The information Lévi gives about these fragments is minimal: he reports having found them at the great Exposition in Paris, in the hands of a merchant from Cairo; but he does not clarify whether he or anyone else purchased them, or what was their subsequent fate. Israel Lévi’s collection was initially deposited in the Consistoire Israélite de Paris, and then transferred, in 1945, to the library of the Alliance Israélite Universelle (AIU). I have searched the collections of the AIU, but to no avail. 

The text of one of Lévi’s fragments, however, was convincingly joined by Mann (1934: 273-7) to Bodl. Heb. d. 74.27 (for which he relied on Guillaume’s edition), and then again (independently) by Sacha Stern, who further joined the other fragment of Lévi with T-S NS 98.18, and hence with the rest of the manuscript.

Guillaume (1915); joined and edited together with most of Schechter’s fragments (T-S 13K2). 

Bornstein (1922b) 259-61: fragment 29 only, based on Guillaume’s edition.

source: Sacha Stern, "The Jewish Calendar Controversy of 921/2 CE," in The Book of the Calendar Controversy: Diplomatic Editions, 1st ed. (2019).
notes:
T-S 13K2.1-2 and 4-6: Schechter (1901-2) 41-3 and 53-59 (reprinted in Schechter 1903). Schechter designated fragments 1, 2, 4, and 5 as Texts IV, IVa, V, Va (respectively); fragment 6 is unnamed and transcribed on p.41.

Guillaume (1915); joined and edited Bodl. Heb. together with most of Schechter’s fragments (T-S 13K2).

source: Sacha Stern, "The Jewish Calendar Controversy of 921/2 CE," in The Book of the Calendar Controversy: Diplomatic Editions, 1st ed. (2019).
notes:
T-S NS 98.18 is unpublished. Sacha Stern discovered it and made the join on 14 July 2014.

Lévi 1900b fgm. 1 is the first of two fragments edited by Israel Lévi (1900b), which may be considered lost. They were re-edited by Bornstein (1904) 87-9.

Lévi only reports having found them at the great Exposition in Paris, in the hands of a merchant from Cairo. His collection was initially deposited in the Consistoire Israélite de Paris, and then transferred, in 1945, to the library of the Alliance Israélite Universelle (AIU). Not found there upon Stern's searching. 

The text was (independently) joined by Sacha Stern, with another fragment of Lévi, T-S NS 98.18, and hence with the rest of the manuscript.
